libpng row padding-bit non-determinism
======================================

Background
----------

Debian bug #1118385 / tex-k discussion (May 2026) reported that pdfTeX
produces different PDF output on consecutive runs when including a
particular PNG image (valuators.png from the fltk1.4 documentation,
567 x 506, 4-bit colormap, non-interlaced) even with
SOURCE_DATE_EPOCH/FORCE_SOURCE_DATE set.

Root cause
----------

For a sub-byte pixel depth (here 4 bpp) and a width that is not a
multiple of 8/bpp (567 * 4 = 2268 bits = 283.5 bytes), the last byte of
each decoded scanline holds the last pixel in its high nibble and 4
padding bits in its low nibble.

In libpng-1.6.58, pngrutil.c:png_combine_row() (non-interlaced path)
deliberately preserves the destination buffer's existing bits in that
padding region:

    end_byte = *end_ptr;                            /* dest bits BEFORE memcpy */
    memcpy(dp, sp, PNG_ROWBYTES(...));              /* whole row from sp       */
    *end_ptr = (end_byte & end_mask)                /* restore dest pad bits   */
             | (*end_ptr & ~end_mask);

pdfTeX allocates its row buffer with xtalloc -> xmalloc (uninitialized
memory). The padding bits in the output PDF therefore reflect whatever
was on the heap at allocation time, so successive runs produce
different bytes for those bits and the PDFs differ.

The PNG specification (W3C PNG, Second Edition, section 7.2
"Scanlines", https://www.w3.org/TR/png/#7Scanline) addresses these
bits explicitly:

    "When there are multiple pixels per byte, some low-order bits of
    the last byte of a scanline may go unused. The contents of these
    unused bits are not specified."

So the spec neither requires encoders to zero them nor permits readers
to rely on any particular value -- they are simply undefined. libpng's
current behaviour of importing them from the caller's destination
buffer is technically conformant, but it is a poor contract: it makes
decoded output depend on uninitialized caller memory, leaking heap
state into downstream consumers and breaking reproducibility for any
caller that does not pre-zero its row buffer.

Fix
---

In libs/libpng/libpng-src/pngrutil.c, png_combine_row() now clears the
padding bits instead of restoring them from the destination buffer:

    if (end_ptr != NULL)
       *end_ptr = (png_byte)(*end_ptr & ~end_mask);

Test program
------------

The file ./pngtest.c (kept outside the libpng tree on purpose; it
links against libpng and is not part of libpng itself) decodes a PNG
three times, pre-filling the user-provided row buffer with 0x00, 0xff,
and 0xaa before each png_read_row(). It prints the last 4 bytes of
the first decoded row for each fill.

  /* see pngtest.c */

The trigger image is available in ./valuators.png, and can be obtained via

    curl -sL "https://salsa.debian.org/fltk-team/fltk1.4/-/raw/main/documentation/src/valuators.png" \
        -o ./valuators.png

Demonstrate the bug against the system (unpatched) libpng:

    gcc pngtest.c -lpng -o pngtest
    ./pngtest valuators.png

Expected (buggy) output -- the low nibble of the last byte mirrors the
fill, proving the destination buffer's bits leak into the decoded row:

    fill=0x00 row0 last bytes: 00 00 00 00
    fill=0xff row0 last bytes: 00 00 00 0f
    fill=0xaa row0 last bytes: 00 00 00 0a

Demonstrate the fix against the patched in-tree libpng (after building
under Build/source/Work):

    gcc pngtest.c \
        -I.../Build/source/libs/libpng/libpng-src \
        -I.../Build/source/Work/libs/libpng \
        .../Build/source/Work/libs/libpng/libpng.a \
        -lz -lm -o pngtest_patched
    ./pngtest_patched valuators.png

Expected (fixed) output -- padding bits are zero regardless of the
caller's buffer contents:

    fill=0x00 row0 last bytes: 00 00 00 00
    fill=0xff row0 last bytes: 00 00 00 00
    fill=0xaa row0 last bytes: 00 00 00 00

Reproducing through pdfTeX
--------------------------

The pngtest.c harness above exhibits the bug directly because it
deliberately memset()s the row buffer with 0x00 / 0xff / 0xaa before
each png_read_row(). In a real pdfTeX run the row buffer is allocated
with xtalloc -> xmalloc, and on a fresh process glibc commonly returns
a freshly mmap'd zero page for small allocations -- so the leaked
padding bits happen to be 0 and successive PDFs are bit-identical even
though the bug is latent. The original bug reporter only observed the
non-determinism because more complex documents churn the heap enough
to leave non-zero remnants in the chunk that ends up backing the row
buffer.

To surface the bug on demand, use glibc's MALLOC_PERTURB_ knob: when
set to N (1..255) it fills every freshly-allocated byte with ~N (and
every freed byte with N). That replaces "whatever happened to be
there" with deterministic non-zero garbage and immediately reveals any
code path reading uninitialised memory.

Minimal example using the trigger image in this directory:

    # create a minimal trigger.png
    python make-trigger.py
    # create the tex file
    cat > trigger.tex <<'EOF'
    \documentclass{article}
    \usepackage{graphicx}
    \begin{document}
    \includegraphics[width=4cm]{trigger.png}
    \end{document}
    EOF
    # make sure usual /ID and other entries are stable
    export SOURCE_DATE_EPOCH=1700000000 FORCE_SOURCE_DATE=1
    # run with malloc perturbation
    for i in 1 2 3; do
        MALLOC_PERTURB_=$((RANDOM % 254 + 1)) \
            pdflatex -interaction=batchmode trigger.tex >/dev/null
        cp trigger.pdf trigger$i.pdf
    done
    sha256sum trigger?.pdf

With an unpatched libpng each invocation produces a different PDF
hash. Fixing MALLOC_PERTURB_ to a constant value also yields a
different (but deterministic) PDF per value, proving the PDF content
depends on the contents of the uninitialised row buffer:

    for v in 0 85 170 255; do
        MALLOC_PERTURB_=$v pdflatex -interaction=batchmode trigger.tex >/dev/null
        echo "MALLOC_PERTURB_=$v $(sha256sum trigger.pdf | cut -c1-16)"
    done

Against a pdfTeX linked to the patched libpng in this tree, all four
hashes are identical regardless of MALLOC_PERTURB_.

Notes
-----

- A pdfTeX-side workaround (memset(row, 0, rowbytes) before each
  png_read_row) would also eliminate the symptom, but the same trap
  exists for every other libpng caller. Fixing libpng once is the
  right layer.
- The fix only changes the non-interlaced memcpy tail in
  png_combine_row(); the interlaced display/sparkle paths are
  untouched.
